SIMPLE: allegation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Allegation
<hw>Al`le*ga"tion</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>allegatio</ets>, fr. <ets>allegare</ets>, <ets>allegatum</ets>, to
send a message, cite; later, to free by giving reasons; <ets>ad</ets> +
<ets>legare</ets> to send, commission. Cf. <er>Allege</er> and
<er>Adlegation</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of alleging or
positively asserting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is alleged, asserted, or declared;
positive assertion; formal averment</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I thought their <qex>allegation</qex> but reasonable.</q>
<rj><qau>Steele.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A statement by a party of what he
undertakes to prove, -- usually applied to each separate averment; the
charge or matter undertaken to be proved.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Allege</ent>⟦br⟧
